iants are also found in Lancashire, England (see   Kirvan  ,   Kirven  ,   Kirvin  ,   Kirwin  ). Compare   Carawan  ."]}]},{"name":"Jan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"Dirks","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Flemish and Dutch form of   Derek .  Its use in the English-speaking world since the 1960s is largely due to the fame of the actor  Dirk Bogarde  (  1921–99 , born  Derek Niven van den Bogaerde ). He was of Dutch descent, although he was actually born in Scotland. The manly image of the name has been reinforced by its coincidence in form with Scottish <i>dirk</i> ‘dagger’ (from Gaelic <i>durc</i>)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jan Dirks Dirven was born in 1372, in Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands, his father, Dirk Dirven, was 28 and his mother, Missy Dirwyf, was 22. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Kathelijn Uten Ghoere. He died in 1442, in his hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1372–1442":"1372–1442","1388–1450":"1388–1450","1390–1449":"1390–1449","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1344–1400":"1344–1400","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1449":"1449","Princenhage, North Brabant, Netherlands":"Princenhage, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Princenhage, Brabant-septentrional, Pays-Bas":"Princenhage, Noord-Brabant, Madalm